<P><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="95%"><TR bgcolor="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#00ff00" FACE="Verdana, Arial">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">saintly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, okay, so using the tutorial as a zone<BR>explorer (with EZE) has a few issues.  A <BR>bunch of zones start you off in a GM teleport<BR>box you can't get out of, or it's dark, or<BR>the dude runs/swims to slow, or whatever.<P>After messing with my tutorial.exe a bit, I<BR>was able to find a way to add a few more<BR>features to it beyond changing the zone file<BR>it loads.  Go nuts...<P>The version of the tutorial I have shows a <BR>Last Modified date of 05/11/1999, and is <BR>1,845,248 bytes long.  The EZE page<BR>mentions other versions, so it would prolly<BR>be a *BAD* idea to go patching offsets in<BR>your tutorial file if your version isn't<BR>the same.<P>You already know where to change the zone,<BR>but just to keep all the info together, I'll<BR>mention it again: There are 11 bytes starting<BR>at offset 19797C where you can put in the<BR>zone you want to load, so long as its <BR>followed by hex 00 (NULL).<P>Change the race of the player at D511C.  It<BR>starts at 01 (Human), to make it Dark Elf<BR>for ultravision, set it to 06.  It will take<BR>values 01-0C for other races and doesn't <BR>know about Iksar.<P>If having to talk to the tutorial mobs<BR>annoys you, get rid of them by patching <BR>offsets D1818-D181C to all hex 90s.<P>Hex code 90 is the assembler instruction<BR>"NOP" (a do-nothing command), so its used<BR>to disable certain instructions.<P>You can have it report your current X,<BR>Y,Z, coords, heading and some other stuff<BR>in your message box:<P>Write hex 90 to offsets: <BR> B3002-7, <BR> B300F-14, <BR> B30E5<BR>Change offset: B2ECD to EB<BR>Starting at offset B30D6, write: <BR> 0D A0 73 70 00 <BR>Change offset: B30DF to 94<BR>Starting at offset B30E7, write: <BR> 90 E8 E3 9C 01 00	   <P>Note: if you combine this with the <BR>flying patch below, it will make it a bit<BR>harder to fly (you have to angle up more<BR>to get off the ground).<P>If you're having trouble exploring the<BR>plane of Sky or whatever, you can allow<BR>the player to fly (like swimming, angle the<BR>view up or down):<BR>At offset D9F7E, change 75 to EB<BR>Change offsets D9FE7-E8 to 90 90<P>Improve the swimming (and flying) speed:<BR>He swims very slow, giving it a 4x increase<BR>makes him swim a little faster than he<BR>walks:<P>At offsets D9FF3-F6 write CD CC 4C 3E<BR>At offsets DA003-06 write CD CC 4C 3F<P>Note, these correspond to the values 0.1<BR>and 0.8.  The first (at D9FF3) controls <BR>the swimming horizontal speed, the second<BR>controls the vertical speed.  If you set<BR>the second to some huge number, like 60<BR>instead of 0.8 you will take huge dolphin<BR>leaps out of the water!  It's hilarious.<BR>You won't be able to explore much underwater<BR>though, since any move that goes up or down<BR>will send you zooming to the top or bottom<BR>of the zone.<P>You can increase the response time for all<BR>movement (making you turn, swim and walk<BR>faster):<BR>At offset 166D48, write in either:<BR>   8FC2 F53C (for a 50% speed increase)<BR>or 0AD7 233D (for a 100% speed increase)<P>Much more than 100% becomes very <BR>disorienting when you turn, but makes moving<BR>long distances a snap.<P>Lastly, you can make it start the zone at<BR>any arbitrary location, but this is a bit<BR>trickier than just pasting in the patches<BR>mentioned above.  <P>To enable this trick, patch all the <BR>following offsets to hex 90:<BR>A8AD-A8B2, A902-A907, A954-A959, A9A6-A9AB, A9F8-A9F9<P>Now you have to get the X,Y,Z coords into <BR>the number format used in the tutorial <BR>program.  This is the IEEE-754 hex <BR>notation with a reversed byte order.<P>There is a web page with a tool that turns<BR>decimal numbers into IEEE-754 notation:<P>http://babbage.cs.qc.edu/courses/cs341/IEEE-754.html<P>It uses javascript, you type in the number<BR>in decimal, click "ROUNDED" and it tells<BR>you the hex code you need to write.  Then<BR>you have to REVERSE the order of what it<BR>says.  Example:<P>You go to the Hole, and you see the message<BR>on the wall: Go to 800, 200, 0.<P>Go to the web page and type in 800, it<BR>comes back with "44480000" (under Hexadecimal<BR>under "Single Precision").  Now reverse the<BR>bytes: 00 00 48 44  (don't just reverse the<BR>individual digits).  Now look up 200: it<BR>comes back with "43480000", that becomes<BR>00 00 48 43.  Zero is still "00000000".<P>Locations for the coords:<BR>X: Offsets C1E32 - C1E35 <BR>Y: Offsets C1E3C - C1E3F <BR>Z: Offsets C1E46 - C1E49 <P>So write 0000 4844 to C1E32, 0000 4843 to<BR>C1E3C, and 0000 0000 to C1E46.<P>It's not *THAT* hard to do, really... it<BR>just sounds difficult until you try it.<P>Once you've patched your tutorial.exe, you<BR>can use EZE to explore different zones <BR>rather than manually editing the zone each<BR>time.  Get EZE from:<P>http://home.tampabay.rr.com/estembler/tristram/eze.htm<P>Have fun...<BR> - The Saint!</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">grimreaver</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Any easy way to patch the offsets (recommendations or anything.... I'm not a programmer, and it's been many many years since I've played with a dos based hex editor hehe)<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">saintly</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Well, one of my friends hopes to write a small windows program that will let you patch the offsets to these and other values (like, to become any race, or adjust the response time to any factor).  With luck, he'll finish this over the weekend.  Not sure where we'll host it though.  For now, manual patching for people a bit rusty:<P>get AXE (Advanced Hex Editor) from:<BR>ftp://ftp.simtel.net/pub/simtelnet/win95/editor/axe20.zip<P>Copy Tutorial.EXE to some other backup name, then open it up in AXE.  Now you see your window divided into 3 columns; Offset, Bytes and Text.  Scroll the file to the closest offset to the one you want to patch, then move your mouse over the bytes (and watch the Offset display on the status line) to get the exact byte to start modifying.  Just put your cursor on that line and type in the patched<BR>values.  If it says to NOP or 90 out a range of offsets, just start at the beginning of the range and change all the hex values to 90 until (and including) the end of the range.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#1f1f1f"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">Grimmier</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">is there a way to change the moveing keys from arrows to W A S D ? and change duck to X ?<P>drives me nuts hehe I play with wasd from my quake config  use the same in EQ but the tutorial annoys me with the arrow keys.</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE>
</FONT>
<SCRIPT LANGUAGE="JavaScript">
<!-- HIDE

var dc = document.cookie;
var testUserName = getCookie("UserName");
var testPassword = getCookie("Password");

if (document.cookie) {

	if (testUserName == null) {  
document.REPLIER.UserName.focus();
	} else {
document.REPLIER.UserName.value = getCookie("UserName");
document.REPLIER.Password.value = getCookie("Password");
document.REPLIER.ReplyMessage.focus();
	}
}  else {
document.REPLIER.UserName.focus();
}
function getCookie(name){
var cname = name + "=";               
var dc = document.cookie;
if (dc.length > 0) {              
    begin = dc.indexOf(cname);
	 if (begin != -1) {           
        begin += cname.length;
		end = dc.indexOf(";", begin);
            if (end == -1) end = dc.length;
            return unescape(dc.substring(begin, end));        }
}
return null;
}

// STOP HIDING FROM OTHER BROWSERS -->
